## Phase 4 Architecture Decisions — Deployment & Data Sources (open, captured 2026-06-15)

Recorded for when the system is proven and ready for blind testing. None of these block current work — NAS remains always-available dev/fallback environment.

### Deployment / hosting
- Target users: multiple people, each on their own machine, working within Azure Virtual Desktop (AVD) sessions, same company tenant.
- **Data-AVD and login-AVD are likely DISTINCT** (same Azure tenant, different AVDs). So the app stays a remote-DB client — same pattern as today (Mac → NAS over Tailscale), just different host/credentials/network path (Azure internal networking / private endpoint).
- AVD-hosting largely dissolves the "standalone compiled installer" concern: provision-once in a controlled image rather than distribute native binaries to varied machines. Users open the app in-session; nobody installs anything.
- **Open topology question:** does Streamlit app run per login-AVD session (one instance each) or on the data-AVD (one shared instance)? Different setup + concurrency implications. Decide later.
- UI framework: staying on Streamlit is reinforced by AVD-hosting (server-viewed-in-browser fits AVD model). Switching shelved unless a concrete limitation bites. HTML-in-Streamlit is the pragmatic path for richer views and transfers to any future framework.

### Data sources
- Current: file ingestion (XML, XLSX, CSV) — narrow coverage so far (1 XML, 2 XLSX, 1 CSV); broadening format test coverage is the near-term priority (under-tested area).
- Future: Halo + Confluence (API access confirmed available — testable when we get there), and Snowflake cloud DB (possibly the primary/only external source).
- **Key architectural principle:** keep the ingestion-source boundary clean so a Snowflake/API/MCP source plugs in as an adapter alongside file parsers, handing rows-with-schema to the existing pipeline. Retrieval/role/serializer layers stay source-agnostic — already the case, must be preserved.

### Guardrail
- Protect the core/UI separation religiously. Business logic (retrieval, schema, serialization) must never leak into ui_app.py. This is the insurance that keeps an eventual UI/framework swap a config-level change, not a rewrite.